`update()` is now `async`, but the main loop still invokes it without awaiting (see `gameLoop()` below). This can render frames before the state update finishes and allow overlapping updates when the `/predict` call is slow. Consider keeping `update()` synchronous, or make the loop await `update()` before `draw()` (and handle the returned Promise).
```suggestion
function update() {
  if (gameState !== 'playing') return;

  if (aiMode && !aiProcessing) {
    aiProcessing = true;
    fetch('/predict', {
      method: 'POST',
      headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
      body: JSON.stringify({
        snake: snake,
        food: food,
        direction: direction
      })
    })
      .then(response => response.json())
      .then(data => {
        const move_idx = data.action; // [straight, right, left]

        const clock_wise = [ {x:1, y:0}, {x:0, y:1}, {x:-1, y:0}, {x:0, y:-1} ];
        let idx = clock_wise.findIndex(d => d.x === direction.x && d.y === direction.y);
        if (idx === -1) idx = 0;

        if (move_idx === 1) nextDirection = clock_wise[(idx + 1) % 4];
        else if (move_idx === 2) nextDirection = clock_wise[(idx + 3) % 4];
        else nextDirection = clock_wise[idx];
      })
      .catch(e => {
        console.error("AI fetch failed", e);
      })
      .finally(() => {
        aiProcessing = false;
      });
  }

  direction = nextDirection;
```
